e of women, enslaved persons, and individuals with disabilities—are punished after death in spaces that mirror real carceral spaces, effectually criminalizing those bodies on earth. Contextualizing the apocalypses alongside ancient medical texts, inscriptions, philosophy, and patristic writings, this book demonstrates the ways that Christian depictions of hell intensified and preserved ancient notions of gender and bodily normativity that continue to inform Christian identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aDamned. 0aFuture lifexChristianity. 0aHellxChristianity. 0aWomenxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / History & Culture.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300262667423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300262667/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles